2:Tb78,{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"Pre-Ride Briefing","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Every T2W ride begins with a mandatory pre-ride briefing. This includes route overview, fuel stop planning, emergency protocols, hand signals review, and rider pairing assignments. Arrive at least 30 minutes before the scheduled departure time."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Formation Riding","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"T2W follows staggered formation on highways and single file on mountain roads. Maintain a 2-second gap from the rider directly ahead. The lead rider sets the pace; never overtake the lead rider. The sweep rider stays at the back at all times."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Hand Signals","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"All T2W riders must know the standard hand signals: left turn (left arm extended), right turn (left arm bent up at 90 degrees), slow down (left arm extended down, palm facing back), stop (left arm bent down at 90 degrees), hazard on road (pointing to the ground), and single file (left index finger raised)."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Mandatory Safety Gear","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"All riders must wear: ISI/ECE certified full-face helmet, riding jacket with armor, riding gloves, riding boots that cover ankles, and riding pants. Hi-visibility vests are recommended for dawn/dusk rides. Non-compliance will result in exclusion from the ride."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Bike Preparation","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Before every ride, perform T-CLOCS check: Tires & Wheels (pressure, tread), Controls (levers, cables, throttle), Lights & Electrics (headlight, tail, indicators), Oil & Fluids (engine oil, coolant, brake fluid), Chassis (frame, suspension), and Stands (side stand, center stand)."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Cornering Techniques","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Slow in, fast out. Reduce speed before entering a corner, not during. Look through the corner to where you want to go. Lean the bike, not your body, for better control. Avoid braking mid-corner. Gradually roll on throttle as you exit the turn."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Emergency Protocol","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"In case of breakdown or accident: Pull over safely to the shoulder. Turn on hazard lights. Place a warning triangle 50m behind the bike. Inform the sweep rider immediately. Do not attempt to move an injured rider. Call emergency services if needed. The sweep rider carries a first-aid kit."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Fuel Management","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Always start a ride with a full tank. Know your bike's range and plan fuel stops accordingly. The ride leader will announce fuel stops. If you notice your fuel is running low, signal the group to stop. Carry a 1-liter emergency fuel reserve on long rides."}}]}0:{"buildId":"1mG1er8fbPUSuzEEu6XQt","rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[[["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"$2"}}],["$","$L3",null,{}]],null,["$","$L4",null,{"children":["$","$5",null,{"name":"Next.MetadataOutlet","children":"$@6"}]}]]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
